In the ''{{ill|Taihei Hyakumonogatari|ja|太平百物語|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', a tale presents Saru-gami in a more eerie, ghostly context: {{Indent|In {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (now northern {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), a samurai staying in a haunted house encountered an old monkey that attacked him in an outhouse. After a fierce struggle, he killed the monkey, discovering numerous human bones in the house, victims of the beast.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Kōji Tokugawa Bun'en|title=Tokugawa Literary Anthology|year=1915|publisher=Kokusho Kankōkai|volume=4|page=367}}</ref>}}
These tales often portray monkeys as both comical and grotesque, reflecting the human tendency to mock creatures that resemble us yet seem less "evolved."<ref name="Nakamura" />
In {{ill|Bizen|ja|備前市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Okayama, and {{ill|Kito|ja|木頭村|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Tokushima, Saru-gami is also considered a {{ill|possession spirit|ja|憑き物|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Those possessed by it are said to become violently uncontrollable, with more severe effects than those of {{ill|Inugami|ja|犬神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Hino Iwao & Hino Yasuhiko|title=Animal Yokai Legends, Vol. 2|year=2006|publisher=Chūōkōron-shinsha|isbn=978-4-12-204792-1|page=268}}</ref>
