[[ja:猿神]] [[sn:Sarugami]] [[en:Sarugami]] [[sn:arugami]] [[zh:%E7%8C%BF%E7%A5%9E]] [[de:Sarugami]]
<!--Sarugami-->

{{ill|sarugami|ja|猿神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} '''Saru-gami''' (猿神) refers to the monkey incarnations considered as messengers of {{ill|sun deities|ja|太陽神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} such as {{ill|Hiyoshi-kami|ja|日吉神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, as well as monkey {{ill|yokai|ja|妖怪|qq=draft|qq=draft}} appearing in Japanese {{ill|medieval|ja|中世|qq=draft|qq=draft}} folktales.
== Belief in Saru-gami == [[File:Hie Shrine Saru-gami.jpg|right|thumb|180px|{{ill|Hie Shrine (Chiyoda)|ja|日枝神社 (千代田区)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Chiyoda, Tokyo, featuring Saru-gami]] {{See also|Japanese macaque#Macaques as mountain deities}}
According to ''Yōtenki'' (耀天記), a Shinto theoretical text attributed to a monk from {{ill|Enryaku-ji|ja|延暦寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on {{ill|Mount Hiei|ja|比叡山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the legendary ancient Chinese figure {{ill|Cangjie|ja|蒼頡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who is said to have invented Chinese characters, learned that before the appearance of gods, {{ill|Shakyamuni|ja|釈迦|qq=draft|qq=draft}} manifested as a deity at {{ill|Hiyoshi Taisha|ja|日吉大社|1=Hiyoshi Taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Japan, taking the form of a monkey to signify omens. This led to the creation of the kanji "神" (god), meaning "to show through the monkey" (申に示す). It is also mentioned that Cangjie was a previous incarnation of Shakyamuni and that soon after his enshrinement at Hiyoshi, monkeys gathered there. Although this story is fictional, it is considered an interesting narrative that connects Buddhist beliefs introduced to Japan with older native Shinto practices, explaining why monkeys were seen as messengers of Hiyoshi-kami.<ref name="Nakamura">{{Harvnb|Nakamura|1989|pp=45-61}}</ref>
In the ancient tale collection ''{{ill|Nihon Ryōiki|ja|日本現報善悪霊異記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', a story describes a monkey appearing to a monk at {{ill|Mount Mikami|ja|三上山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Ōmi Province|ja|近江国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Yasu, Shiga|ja|野洲市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). The monkey claims it was once a king in India, reborn due to past sins as a monkey deity at a local shrine. Since Yasu is located across from Hiyoshi Taisha, it is believed that monkey worship spread around southern Lake Biwa from the 8th to 9th centuries, eventually influencing the view of monkeys as divine messengers in the medieval period.<ref name="Nakamura" />
Although Saru-gami has aspects of a sun deity, with "Hiyoshi" relating to the sun, the connection may also stem from monkeys' tendency to be active at sunrise. This association led to the belief that monkeys played a role in controlling the sun.<ref name="Nakamura" /><ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Tada Katsumi|title=Gensō Sekai no Jūnin-tachi IV|year=1990|publisher=Shinkigensha|isbn=978-4-915146-44-2|page=83}}</ref> However, as people moved away from agricultural lifestyles, the solar aspects of Saru-gami diminished.<ref name="Nakamura" />
During the spread of {{ill|Sannō Shinto|ja|山王信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft}} from the medieval to early modern periods, monkeys retained their role as divine messengers<ref name="Shinohara">{{Harvnb|Shinohara et al.|1986|p=712}}</ref> and were revered as mountain deities.<ref name="Kotanicho">{{Harvnb|Kotanicho et al.|1999|p=292}}</ref> The mediating role of Saru-gami between heaven and earth also linked it with local protective spirits, especially {{ill|Kōshin belief|ja|庚申信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sai no Kami|ja|塞の神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Jizō faith in Japan|ja|地蔵菩薩#日本における地蔵信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="Shinohara" /> In Kōshin belief, the connection to monkeys ("申") inspired the widespread depiction of the {{ill|Three Wise Monkeys|ja|三猿|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on {{ill|Kōshin-tō|ja|庚申塔|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="Shinohara" /><ref name="Kotanicho" />
According to the ''{{ill|Ehon Taikōki|ja|絵本太閤記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s mother dreamed of the sun entering her womb after praying to Hiyoshi-kami, leading to Hideyoshi's conception. The fact that Hideyoshi was nicknamed "Saru" (monkey) may be related to the Hiyoshi and Saru-gami beliefs.<ref name="Nakamura" />
