In the ''{{ill|Taihei Hyakumonogatari|ja|太平百物語|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taihei Hyakumonogatari|qq=}}'', a tale presents Saru-gami in a more eerie, ghostly context: {{Indent|In {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noto Province|qq=}} (now northern {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikawa Prefecture|qq=}}), a samurai staying in a haunted house encountered an old monkey that attacked him in an outhouse. After a fierce struggle, he killed the monkey, discovering numerous human bones in the house, victims of the beast.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Kōji Tokugawa Bun'en|title=Tokugawa Literary Anthology|year=1915|publisher=Kokusho Kankōkai|volume=4|page=367}}</ref>}}
These tales often portray monkeys as both comical and grotesque, reflecting the human tendency to mock creatures that resemble us yet seem less "evolved."<ref name="Nakamura" />
