According to the ''{{ill|Ehon Taikōki|ja|絵本太閤記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ehon Taikōki|qq=}}'', {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotomi Hideyoshi|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=}}'s mother dreamed of the sun entering her womb after praying to Hiyoshi-kami, leading to Hideyoshi's conception. The fact that Hideyoshi was nicknamed "Saru" (monkey) may be related to the Hiyoshi and Saru-gami beliefs.<ref name="Nakamura" />

== Saru-gami as a Yokai ==
[[File:Konjaku Monogatarishu Sarugami.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Saru-gami exorcism from the ''{{ill|Konjaku Monogatarishū|ja|今昔物語集|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konjaku Monogatarishū|qq=}}'']]
In medieval Japanese folktales such as ''Konjaku Monogatarishū'' and ''{{ill|Uji Shūi Monogatari|ja|宇治拾遺物語|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uji Shūi Monogatari|qq=}}'', Saru-gami appears as a malevolent {{ill|yokai|ja|妖怪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yokai|qq=}}. A well-known story from ''Konjaku Monogatarishū'' describes a monkey demanding human sacrifices:
{{Indent|In {{ill|Mimasaka Province|ja|美作国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mimasaka Province|qq=}} (present-day {{ill|Okayama Prefecture|ja|岡山県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okayama Prefecture|qq=}}), a giant monkey deity demanded an annual human female sacrifice. When a young girl was chosen, a visiting hunter volunteered to take her place. Hiding inside a chest with his trained dogs, the hunter ambushed the giant monkey and its followers, defeating them. The chief monkey spirit, possessing a shrine priest, pleaded for mercy, promising to end the sacrifices. The hunter spared it, and the ritual ceased thereafter.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Unknown|editor=Satake Akihiro et al.|title=Konjaku Monogatarishū|year=1996|publisher=Iwanami Shoten|isbn=978-4-00-240037-2|pages=28-33}}</ref>}}

After losing its divine status, Saru-gami was often mocked in folklore. A humorous example from the Muromachi period’s ''Fuji Bukuro no Sōshi'' illustrates this:
{{Indent|In {{ill|Ōmi Province|ja|近江国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmi Province|qq=}}, an old man joked that he'd marry off his daughter to anyone who helped with farm work—even a monkey. A giant monkey appeared, helped with the work, and later abducted the daughter as promised. A nobleman rescued her, replacing her with a dog in a bag. The monkey returned, only to be killed by the dog.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Takashima Masae|title=Japanese Fairy Tales: Interesting Stories|year=1952|publisher=Chōbunkan|pages=59-63}}</ref>}}

Similar tales across Japan depict Saru-gami demanding sacrifices and being defeated by hunters or monks, often with the aid of dogs.<ref name="Murakami">{{Harvnb|Murakami|2005|p=157}}</ref> This motif echoes the {{ill|Yamata no Orochi|ja|ヤマタノオロチ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamata no Orochi|qq=}} myth, believed to stem from ancient marriage rituals between deities and priestesses.<ref name="Nakamura" /> Notably, these stories often feature sacred dogs, such as {{ill|Hayatarō|ja|光前寺#早太郎説話|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hayatarō|qq=}} from {{ill|Kōzen-ji|ja|光前寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōzen-ji|qq=}} in Nagano, famed for defeating monsters like {{ill|hibagon|ja|狒々|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/hibagon|qq=}}.<ref name="Murakami" />

In the ''{{ill|Taihei Hyakumonogatari|ja|太平百物語|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taihei Hyakumonogatari|qq=}}'', a tale presents Saru-gami in a more eerie, ghostly context:
{{Indent|In {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noto Province|qq=}} (now northern {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikawa Prefecture|qq=}}), a samurai staying in a haunted house encountered an old monkey that attacked him in an outhouse. After a fierce struggle, he killed the monkey, discovering numerous human bones in the house, victims of the beast.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Kōji Tokugawa Bun'en|title=Tokugawa Literary Anthology|year=1915|publisher=Kokusho Kankōkai|volume=4|page=367}}</ref>}}

These tales often portray monkeys as both comical and grotesque, reflecting the human tendency to mock creatures that resemble us yet seem less "evolved."<ref name="Nakamura" />

In {{ill|Bizen|ja|備前市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bizen|qq=}}, Okayama, and {{ill|Kito|ja|木頭村|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kito|qq=}}, Tokushima, Saru-gami is also considered a {{ill|possession spirit|ja|憑き物|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/possession spirit|qq=}}. Those possessed by it are said to become violently uncontrollable, with more severe effects than those of {{ill|Inugami|ja|犬神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inugami|qq=}}.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Hino Iwao & Hino Yasuhiko|title=Animal Yokai Legends, Vol. 2|year=2006|publisher=Chūōkōron-shinsha|isbn=978-4-12-204792-1|page=268}}</ref>

