During the spread of {{ill|Sannō Shinto|ja|山王信仰|1=Sannō Faith|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sannō Shinto|qq=}} from the medieval to early modern periods, monkeys retained their role as divine messengers<ref name="Shinohara">{{Harvnb|Shinohara et al.|1986|p=712}}</ref> and were revered as mountain deities.<ref name="Kotanicho">{{Harvnb|Kotanicho et al.|1999|p=292}}</ref> The mediating role of Saru-gami between heaven and earth also linked it with local protective spirits, especially [[:en:Kōshin|Kōshin belief]], {{ill|Sai no Kami|ja|塞の神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sai no Kami|qq=}}, and {{ill|Jizō faith in Japan|ja|地蔵菩薩#日本における地蔵信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jizō faith in Japan|qq=}}.<ref name="Shinohara" /> In Kōshin belief, the connection to monkeys ("申") inspired the widespread depiction of the [[:en:Three wise monkeys|Three Wise Monkeys]] on {{ill|Kōshin-tō|ja|庚申塔|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōshin-tō|qq=}}.<ref name="Shinohara" /><ref name="Kotanicho" />
According to the ''{{ill|Ehon Taikōki|ja|絵本太閤記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ehon Taikōki|qq=}}'', [[:en:Toyotomi Hideyoshi|Toyotomi Hideyoshi]]'s mother dreamed of the sun entering her womb after praying to Hiyoshi-kami, leading to Hideyoshi's conception. The fact that Hideyoshi was nicknamed "Saru" (monkey) may be related to the Hiyoshi and Saru-gami beliefs.<ref name="Nakamura" />
== Saru-gami as a Yokai == [[File:Konjaku Monogatarishu Sarugami.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Saru-gami exorcism from the ''[[:en:Konjaku Monogatarishū|Konjaku Monogatarishū]]'']] In medieval Japanese folktales such as ''Konjaku Monogatarishū'' and ''[[:en:Uji Shūi Monogatari|Uji Shūi Monogatari]]'', Saru-gami appears as a malevolent [[:en:Yōkai|yokai]]. A well-known story from ''Konjaku Monogatarishū'' describes a monkey demanding human sacrifices: {{Indent|In [[:en:Mimasaka Province|Mimasaka Province]] (present-day [[:en:Okayama Prefecture|Okayama Prefecture]]), a giant monkey deity demanded an annual human female sacrifice. When a young girl was chosen, a visiting hunter volunteered to take her place. Hiding inside a chest with his trained dogs, the hunter ambushed the giant monkey and its followers, defeating them. The chief monkey spirit, possessing a shrine priest, pleaded for mercy, promising to end the sacrifices. The hunter spared it, and the ritual ceased thereafter.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Unknown|editor=Satake Akihiro et al.|title=Konjaku Monogatarishū|year=1996|publisher=Iwanami Shoten|isbn=978-4-00-240037-2|pages=28-33}}</ref>}}
After losing its divine status, Saru-gami was often mocked in folklore. A humorous example from the Muromachi period’s ''Fuji Bukuro no Sōshi'' illustrates this: {{Indent|In [[:en:Ōmi Province|Ōmi Province]], an old man joked that he'd marry off his daughter to anyone who helped with farm work—even a monkey. A giant monkey appeared, helped with the work, and later abducted the daughter as promised. A nobleman rescued her, replacing her with a dog in a bag. The monkey returned, only to be killed by the dog.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Takashima Masae|title=Japanese Fairy Tales: Interesting Stories|year=1952|publisher=Chōbunkan|pages=59-63}}</ref>}}
Similar tales across Japan depict Saru-gami demanding sacrifices and being defeated by hunters or monks, often with the aid of dogs.<ref name="Murakami">{{Harvnb|Murakami|2005|p=157}}</ref> This motif echoes the [[:en:Yamata no Orochi|Yamata no Orochi]] myth, believed to stem from ancient marriage rituals between deities and priestesses.<ref name="Nakamura" /> Notably, these stories often feature sacred dogs, such as {{ill|Hayatarō|ja|光前寺#早太郎説話|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hayatarō|qq=}} from [[:en:Kōzen-ji|Kōzen-ji]] in Nagano, famed for defeating monsters like {{ill|hibagon|ja|狒々|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/hibagon|qq=}}.<ref name="Murakami" />
In the ''{{ill|Taihei Hyakumonogatari|ja|太平百物語|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taihei Hyakumonogatari|qq=}}'', a tale presents Saru-gami in a more eerie, ghostly context: {{Indent|In [[:en:Noto Province|Noto Province]] (now northern [[:en:Ishikawa Prefecture|Ishikawa Prefecture]]), a samurai staying in a haunted house encountered an old monkey that attacked him in an outhouse. After a fierce struggle, he killed the monkey, discovering numerous human bones in the house, victims of the beast.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Kōji Tokugawa Bun'en|title=Tokugawa Literary Anthology|year=1915|publisher=Kokusho Kankōkai|volume=4|page=367}}</ref>}}
These tales often portray monkeys as both comical and grotesque, reflecting the human tendency to mock creatures that resemble us yet seem less "evolved."<ref name="Nakamura" />
In [[:en:Bizen, Okayama|Bizen]], Okayama, and [[:en:Kito, Tokushima|Kito]], Tokushima, Saru-gami is also considered a {{ill|possession spirit|ja|憑き物|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/possession spirit|qq=}}. Those possessed by it are said to become violently uncontrollable, with more severe effects than those of [[:en:Inugami|Inugami]].<ref>{{Cite book|ja|author=Hino Iwao & Hino Yasuhiko|title=Animal Yokai Legends, Vol. 2|year=2006|publisher=Chūōkōron-shinsha|isbn=978-4-12-204792-1|page=268}}</ref>
